es and operations of the 1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]]\n[[Category:1948 Palestinian exodus|Arab-Israeli War]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n", "name_user": "EdMcCorduck", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed text \"Arabs opposition\" in second paragraph to \"Arab opposition\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1948_Arab%E2%80%93Israeli_War"}
{"title_page": "C. W. Nicol", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Welsh-born Japanese writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = C. W. Nicol\n| image        = C.W. Nicol - Headshot in Afan Woodland.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = Clive William Nicol\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1940|07|17}}\n| birth_place   = Neath, Wales, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|03|1940|07|17}}\n| death_place   = Nagano, Japan\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer, illustrator\n| nationality  = [[Welsh people|Welsh]], [[British people|British]]\n| citizenship  = Japanese\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = [[Tokyo University of Science]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| signature_alt = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n'''Clive William Nicol''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] ({{Lang-ja|C\u30fbW\u30fb\u30cb\u30b3\u30eb}}; 17 July 1940 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a British-born Japanese writer, singer/songwriter, and actor. He was a long-time resident and citizen of [[Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html# |title=An Interview with C W Nicol |access-date=23 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108083613/http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html# |archive-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nC. W. Nicol was born in [[Neath]], [[Wales]] in July 1940.\n\nHe graduated from [[Tokyo University of Science]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1958 he visited the [[Arctic Circle]] to research [[eider duck]]. He became a [[Canada|Canadian]] citizen. By the early 1960s he was studying [[Shotokan]] [[karate]]-Do at the headquarters of the [[Japan Karate Association]] (JKA) and studied [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[fishery|fisheries]] at [[Nihon University]]. He spent 1967 to 1969 as a game warden in [[Ethiopia]], setting up the new [[Semien Mountains National Park]]. He returned to Japan, writing a book about his Ethiopian experiences entitled ''From the Roof of Africa'' (1971).\n\nSince taking up residence in Japan he wrote books and other literary works. In 1980 he won the Japan Broadcasting Writer's Award for a television drama written in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]. He continued to be an active [[environmentalist]] and lecture about the environment, addressing issues such as [[deforestation]] and the preservation of natural environments. He was particularly interested in restoring Japan's vast [[woodland]]s. The C. W. Nicol Afan Woodland in Kurohime, [[Shinano, Nagano|Shinano]]machi, Nagano Prefecture, was established in 1986.\n\nHe became a Japanese citizen (and thus lost his Canadian and British citizenship), which he wrote about in {{nihongo|''Why I became Japanese''|\u50d5\u304c\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f\u7406\u7531|Boku ga Nihonjin ni natta riy\u016b}}.\n\nHe wrote both fiction and non-fiction books, in both Japanese and in English. His subjects included [[whaling]] (for which he went on a trip on a whaling vessel), the environment, martial arts and children's fiction. His books have been translated between English and Japanese, as well as into [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[German language|German]], [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], [[Korean language|Korean]] and [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. In 2005, he was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire]].\n\nC. W. Nicol was the chairman of the Afan Woodland Trust. He was diagnosed with cancer in 2016, and died aged 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2020/04/04/environment/c-w-nicol-uncompromising-environmentalist-possessed-deep-humanity/|title=C.W. Nicol, a committed environmentalist with deep humanity|date=4 April 2020|author=Andrew Kershaw|website=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''The White Shaman''\n*''Harpoon / Isana''\n*''[[The Boy Who Saw the Wind]]''\n*''The Raven's Tale''\n*''From the Roof of Africa''\n*''Moving Zen: Karate as a Way to Gentleness''\n*''The White Hippo''\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Sail Down the River]]'' (1991)\n* ''The World of Little Twins'' (1992)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hideo Levy]]<!--Other non-native Japanese author.-->\n* [[David Zoppetti]]<!--Other non-native Japanese author.-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official site|http://www.cwnicol.com}}\n*[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life_column/old-nics-notebook Old Nic's Notebook : Japan Times]\n*[http://afan.or.jp Afan Woodland Trust]\n*[http://www.abcbookworld.com/?state=view_author&author_id=218 Short Biography at abcbookworld]\n*[http://www.koemagazine.com/2012/03/cw-nicol/ Ko-e Magazine Interview]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/3032210.stm BBC News: Green mission for karate master]\n*[http://www.outsideonline.com/outdoor-adventure/He-s-Big--He-s-Bad--He-s---Japanese-.html?page=all Jeffrey Bartholet, He's Big, He's Bad, He's...Japanese? Running wild with C. W. Nicol, proud citizen, silly celebrity, and stubborn environmentalist] ''Outside''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150108083613/http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html An Interview with C.W. Nicol: Warrior of Peace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicol, C.W.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese environmentalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male writers]]\n[[Category:Shotokan practitioners]]\n[[Category:After Dark (British TV series) participants]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh male karateka]]\n[[Category:People who lost Canadian citizenship]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Japan]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Nihon University alumni]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to Japan]]\n[[Category:People who lost British citizenship]]\n[[Category:Welsh male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Neath]]\n[[Category:Tokyo University of Science alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|Welsh-born Japanese writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = C. W. Nicol\n| image        = C.W. Nicol - Headshot in Afan Woodland.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = Clive William Nicol\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1940|07|17}}\n| birth_place   = Neath, Wales, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2020|04|03|1940|07|17}}\n| death_place   = Nagano, Japan\n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Writer, illustrator\n| nationality  = [[Welsh people|Welsh]], [[British people|British]]\n| citizenship  = Japanese\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = [[Tokyo University of Science]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| signature_alt = \n| website      = \n| portaldisp   = \n}}\n'''Clive William Nicol''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] ({{Lang-ja|C\u30fbW\u30fb\u30cb\u30b3\u30eb}}; 17 July 1940 \u2013 3 April 2020) was a British-born Japanese writer, singer/songwriter, and actor. He was a long-time resident and citizen of [[Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html# |title=An Interview with C W Nicol |access-date=23 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108083613/http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html# |archive-date=8 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n\n==Early life==\nC. W. Nicol was born in [[Neath]], [[Wales]] in July 1940.\n\nHe graduated from [[Tokyo University of Science]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1958 he visited the [[Arctic Circle]] to research [[eider duck]]. He became a [[Canada|Canadian]] citizen. By the early 1960s he was studying [[Shotokan]] [[karate]]-Do at the headquarters of the [[Japan Karate Association]] (JKA) and studied [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[fishery|fisheries]] at [[Nihon University]]. He spent 1967 to 1969 as a game warden in [[Ethiopia]], setting up the new [[Semien Mountains National Park]]. He returned to Japan, writing a book about his Ethiopian experiences entitled ''From the Roof of Africa'' (1971).\n\nSince taking up residence in Japan he wrote books and other literary works. In 1980 he won the Japan Broadcasting Writer's Award for a television drama written in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]. He continued to be an active [[environmentalist]] and lecture about the environment, addressing issues such as [[deforestation]] and the preservation of natural environments. He was particularly interested in restoring Japan's vast [[woodland]]s. The C. W. Nicol Afan Woodland in Kurohime, [[Shinano, Nagano|Shinano]]machi, Nagano Prefecture, was established in 1986.\n\nHe became a Japanese citizen (and thus lost his Canadian and British citizenship), which he wrote about in {{nihongo|''Why I became Japanese''|\u50d5\u304c\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305f\u7406\u7531|Boku ga Nihonjin ni natta riy\u016b}}.\n\nHe wrote both fiction and non-fiction books, in both Japanese and in English. His subjects included [[whaling]] (for which he went on a trip on a whaling vessel), the environment, martial arts and children's fiction. His books have been translated between English and Japanese, as well as into [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[German language|German]], [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], [[Korean language|Korean]] and [[Chinese language|Chinese]]. In 2005, he was awarded an [[Order of the British Empire]].\n\nC. W. Nicol was the chairman of the Afan Woodland Trust. He was diagnosed with cancer in 2016, and died aged 79.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/life/2020/04/04/environment/c-w-nicol-uncompromising-environmentalist-possessed-deep-humanity/|title=C.W. Nicol, a committed environmentalist with deep humanity|date=4 April 2020|author=Andrew Kershaw|website=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''The White Shaman''\n*''Harpoon / Isana''\n*''[[The Boy Who Saw the Wind]]''\n*''The Raven's Tale''\n*''From the Roof of Africa''\n*''Moving Zen: Karate as a Way to Gentleness''\n*''The White Hippo''\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Sail Down the River]]'' (1991)\n* ''The World of Little Twins'' (1992)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Hideo Levy]]<!--Other non-native Japanese author.-->\n* [[David Zoppetti]]<!--Other non-native Japanese author.-->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official site|http://www.cwnicol.com}}\n*[http://www.japantimes.co.jp/life_column/old-nics-notebook Old Nic's Notebook : Japan Times]\n*[http://afan.or.jp Afan Woodland Trust]\n*[http://www.abcbookworld.com/?state=view_author&author_id=218 Short Biography at abcbookworld]\n*[http://www.koemagazine.com/2012/03/cw-nicol/ Ko-e Magazine Interview]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/3032210.stm BBC News: Green mission for karate master]\n*[http://www.outsideonline.com/outdoor-adventure/He-s-Big--He-s-Bad--He-s---Japanese-.html?page=all Jeffrey Bartholet, He's Big, He's Bad, He's...Japanese? Running wild with C. W. Nicol, proud citizen, silly celebrity, and stubborn environmentalist] ''Outside''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150108083613/http://www.theshotokanway.com/aninterviewwithcwnicolp1.html An Interview with C.W. Nicol: Warrior of Peace]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicol, C.W.}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Exophonic writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese environmentalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male writers]]\n[[Category:Shotokan practitioners]]\n[[Category:After Dark (British TV series) participants]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:Welsh male karateka]]\n[[Category:People who lost Canadian citizenship]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Japan]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Nihon University alumni]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to Japan]]\n[[Category:People who lost British citizenship]]\n[[Category:Welsh male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Neath]]\n[[Category:Tokyo University of Science alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._W._Nicol"}
{"title_page": "Paipai language", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Ba Pai language}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Paipai\n|nativename=''Akwa'ala''\n|region=[[Mexico]]\n|ethnicity= [[Paipai people]]\n|speakers  = 200\n|date=2010 census\n|ref=inali\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Yuman languages|Yuman]]\n|fam2=Core Yuman\n|fam3=Pai ?\n|iso3=ppi\n|glotto=paip1241\n|glottorefname=Paipai\n}}\n'''Paipai''' is the native language of the [[Paipai]]. It is part of the [[Yuman languages|Yuman]] language family. There are very few speakers left because most Paipai now live in [[Kumeyaay]] villages.\n\nIt is believed that [[Paipai]] was separated from the ''Northern Pai languages'' many years ago. In oral tradition of most [[Yuman]] tribes, the people descended from [[Spirit Mountain (Nevada)|Avikwame]] (also known as Newberry Mt.) and went were [[Kumat]] directed them. So at one time the [[Paipai]] might have been with the other tribes.\n\nThe Paipai language was documented by Judith Jo\u00ebl and  Mauricio J. Mixco, who have published texts and studies of syntax.\n[[File:WIKITONGUES- Armandina speaking Paipai.webm|thumb|Video of Armandina Gonz\u00e1lez speaking Paipai produced for [[Wikitongues]]]]\n\nPaipai belongs to the [[Yuman languages|Yuman]] language family. Within the Yuman family, Paipai belongs to the Pai branch, which also includes the [[Upland Yuman language]], dialects of which are spoken by the [[Yavapai people|Yavapai]], [[Hualapai|Walapai]], and [[Havasupai]] of western Arizona. The relationship between Paipai and Upland Yuman is very close; some observers have suggested that Paipai and Yavapai are mutually intelligible (i.e., that the Paipai and Upland Yumans spoke dialects of a single language), while other observers have claimed that they are not.\n\nThe controversial technique of [[glottochronology]] suggests that the Pai branch of Yuman may have separated from the other two branches of Core Yuman (River Yuman and Delta\u2013California Yuman) about 1,000-1,700 years ago. Paipai may have separated from Upland Yuman 1,000 years ago or less.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hokan languages}}\n{{Languages of Mexico}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paipai Language}}\n[[Category:Yuman\u2013Cochim\u00ed languages]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of the North American Southwest]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Ba Pai language}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Paipai\n|nativename=Akwa'ala\n|region=[[Mexico]]\n|ethnicity= [[Paipai people]]\n|speakers  = 200\n|date=2010 census\n|ref=inali\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Yuman languages|Yuman]]\n|fam2=Core Yuman\n|fam3=Pai ?\n|iso3=ppi\n|glotto=paip1241\n|glottorefname=Paipai\n}}\n'''Paipai''' is the native language of the [[Paipai]]. It is part of the [[Yuman languages|Yuman]] language family. There are very few speakers left because most Paipai now live in [[Kumeyaay]] villages.\n\nIt is believed that [[Paipai]] was separated from the ''Northern Pai languages'' many years ago. In oral tradition of most [[Yuman]] tribes, the people descended from [[Spirit Mountain (Nevada)|Avikwame]] (also known as Newberry Mt.) and went were [[Kumat]] directed them. So at one time the [[Paipai]] might have been with the other tribes.\n\nThe Paipai language was documented by Judith Jo\u00ebl and  Mauricio J. Mixco, who have published texts and studies of syntax.\n[[File:WIKITONGUES- Armandina speaking Paipai.webm|thumb|Video of Armandina Gonz\u00e1lez speaking Paipai produced for [[Wikitongues]]]]\n\nPaipai belongs to the [[Yuman languages|Yuman]] language family. Within the Yuman family, Paipai belongs to the Pai branch, which also includes the [[Upland Yuman language]], dialects of which are spoken by the [[Yavapai people|Yavapai]], [[Hualapai|Walapai]], and [[Havasupai]] of western Arizona. The relationship between Paipai and Upland Yuman is very close; some observers have suggested that Paipai and Yavapai are mutually intelligible (i.e., that the Paipai and Upland Yumans spoke dialects of a single language), while other observers have claimed that they are not.\n\nThe controversial technique of [[glottochronology]] suggests that the Pai branch of Yuman may have separated from the other two branches of Core Yuman (River Yuman and Delta\u2013California Yuman) about 1,000-1,700 years ago. Paipai may have separated from Upland Yuman 1,000 years ago or less.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Hokan languages}}\n{{Languages of Mexico}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paipai Language}}\n[[Category:Yuman\u2013Cochim\u00ed languages]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Indigenous languages of the North American Southwest]]\n", "name_user": "Liggliluff", "label": "safe", "comment": "nativename in cursive", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paipai_language"}
